  "type": "mcq",
  "title": "Isolines and E field",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH961883.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Suppose we wish to represent the electric potential around <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q sub 1 \"><math alttext=\"Q sub 1 \" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q sub 2\"><math alttext=\"Q sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> by drawing isolines. What is the relationship of the isolines of electric potential to the net electric field vectors in the region around <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q sub 1 \"><math alttext=\"Q sub 1 \" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q sub 2\"><math alttext=\"Q sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i3",
    "choices": [
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The isolines are always directed along the electric field vectors.</p>",
        "value": "i1"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The isolines are always opposite the electric field vectors.</p>",
        "value": "i2"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The isolines are always perpendicular to the electric field vectors.</p>",
        "value": "i3"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The isolines are perpendicular to the electric field vectors when the field is uniform, but they can be at any angle to the vectors when the field is nonuniform.</p>",
        "value": "i4"
      }
    ]
  },
